{
  "version": 2,
  "name": "VoronoiPrism",
  "description": "Voronoi Prism, decomposed: a beat-reseeded per-cell temporal composite built from atoms. node.voronoi_2d partitions into cells and emits each pixel's cell coordinate on its cell_id output (the same atom StarField uses for F1/F2/cell_hash — no separate partition); node.math(Floor) on generator_input.beat gives the integer beat used as a re-hash seed; two node.hash_field_by_seed re-roll a per-cell UV offset (hash2) and per-cell visibility (hash1) each beat. The offset (scaled to ±0.2) is added to a node.uv_strip_clamp content-window UV and node.remap samples the source there. node.beat_ramp fades cells in over the first 15% of each beat; node.smoothstep_texture thresholds ~60% of cells visible; node.gain multiplies visibility by the pop-in; node.mix(Multiply) darkens the prism by visibility (dark cells go black) and node.mix(Lerp, amount) crossfades over the source. Replaces the fused node.voronoi_prism. Two reusable atoms (hash_field_by_seed, beat_ramp) plus the cell_id output added to the shared node.voronoi_2d (the old single-use node.voronoi_cell_id is deleted). It is a visual reconstruction, not a bit-port. Documented deltas (visual effect, verified by eye): cell layout now comes from voronoi_2d's wang-hash partition (cells square in UV, not aspect-corrected to square-in-pixels as the legacy hash2 partition was) rather than the prism's bespoke partition — same beat-reseeded behaviour, different exact cell shapes; and the post-offset UV is clamped to [0,1] by remap rather than re-clamped to the content strip, so cell edges may pull in a little out-of-strip source.",
